<H3>The Nobel Prize in Economic Sciences 1969</H3>
<!--misc-->
<!--misc-->The 
<!--misc-->prize 
<!--misc-->was 
<!--misc-->awarded 
<!--misc-->jointly 
<!--misc-->to:
<p>
<!--misc-->
<!--name-->FRISCH, 
<!--name-->RAGNAR, 
<!--misc-->Norway, 
<!--misc-->Oslo 
<!--misc-->University, 

<!--misc-->and
<p>
<!--misc-->
<!--name-->TINBERGEN, 
<!--name-->JAN, 
<!--misc-->The 
<!--misc-->Netherlands, 
<!--misc-->The 
<!--misc-->Netherlands 
<!--misc-->School 
<!--misc-->of 
<!--misc-->Economics, 
<!--misc-->Rotterdam, 
<!--english motivation--> "for having developed and applied dynamic models for the analysis of  economic processes".
<!--misc-->
<p>
<!--misc-->
<H3>The Nobel Prize in Economic Sciences 1970</H3>
<!--misc-->
<!--name-->SAMUELSON, 
<!--name-->PAUL 
<!--misc-->A, 
<!--misc-->U.S.A., 
<!--misc-->Massachusetts 
<!--misc-->Institute 
<!--misc-->of 
<!--misc-->Technology, 
<!--misc-->Cambridge 
<!--name-->(MIT), 
<!--name-->MA, 
<!--english motivation--> "for  the scientific work through which he has developed static and dynamic economic theory and actively contributed to raising the level of analysis in  economic science".
<!--misc-->
<p>
<!--misc-->
<H3>The Nobel Prize in Economic Sciences 1971</H3>
<!--misc-->
<!--name-->KUZNETS, 
<!--name-->SIMON, 
<!--misc-->U.S.A., 
<!--misc-->Harvard 
<!--misc-->University, 
<!--misc-->Cambridge, 
<!--name-->MA, 
<!--english motivation-->"for  his empirically founded interpretation of economic growth which has led to new and deepened insight into the economic and social structure and  process of development".
<!--misc-->
<p>
<!--misc-->
<H3>The Nobel Prize in Economic Sciences 1972</H3>
<!--misc-->
<!--misc-->The 
<!--misc-->prize 
<!--misc-->was 
<!--misc-->awarded 
<!--misc-->jointly 
<!--misc-->to:
<p>
<!--misc-->
<!--name-->HICKS, 
<!--misc-->Sir 
<!--name-->JOHN 
<!--misc-->R., 
<!--misc-->Great 
<!--misc-->Britain, 
<!--misc-->All 
<!--misc-->Souls 
<!--misc-->College,
<!--misc-->Oxford, 
<!--misc-->and
<p>
<!--misc-->
<!--name-->ARROW, 
<!--name-->KENNETH 
<!--misc-->J., 
<!--misc-->U.S.A., 
<!--misc-->Harvard 
<!--misc-->University, 
<!--misc-->Cambridge, 
<!--name-->MA, 
<!--english motivation--> "for their pioneering contributions to general economic equilibrium theory and welfare theory".
<!--misc-->
<p>
<!--misc-->
<H3>The Nobel Prize in Economic Sciences 1973</H3>
<!--misc-->
<!--name-->LEONTIEF, 
<!--name-->WASSILY, 
<!--misc-->U.S.A., 
<!--misc-->Harvard 
<!--misc-->University,
<!--misc-->Cambridge, 
<!--name-->MA, 
<!--english motivation--> "for the development of  the input-output method and for its application to important economic problems".
<!--misc-->
<p>
<!--misc-->
<H3>The Nobel Prize in Economic Sciences 1974</H3>
<!--misc-->
<!--misc-->The 
<!--misc-->prize 
<!--misc-->was 
<!--misc-->divided 
<!--misc-->equally 
<!--misc-->between:
<p>
<!--misc-->
<!--name-->MYRDAL, 
<!--name-->GUNNAR, 
<!--misc-->Sweden, 
<!--misc-->and
<p>
<!--misc-->
<!--name-->VON 
<!--name-->HAYEK, 
<!--name-->FRIEDRICH 
<!--name-->AUGUST, 
<!--misc-->Great 
<!--misc-->Britain,
<!--english motivation--> "for their pioneering work in the theory of money and economic fluctuations  and for their penetrating analysis of the interdependence of economic, social and institutional phenomena".
<!--misc-->
<p>
<!--misc-->
<H3>The Nobel Prize in Economic Sciences 1975</H3>
<!--misc-->
<!--misc-->The 
<!--misc-->prize 
<!--misc-->was 
<!--misc-->awarded 
<!--misc-->jointly 
<!--misc-->to:
<p>
<!--misc-->
<!--name-->KANTOROVICH, 
<!--name-->LEONID 
<!--name-->VITALIYEVICH, 
<!--name-->USSR,

<!--misc-->Academy 
<!--misc-->of 
<!--misc-->Sciences, 
<!--misc-->Moscow, 
<!--misc-->and
<p>
