<!--name-->KOOPMANS, 
<!--name-->TJALLING 
<!--misc-->C., 
<!--misc-->U.S.A., 
<!--misc-->Yale 
<!--misc-->University, 
<!--misc-->New 
<!--misc-->Haven, 
<!--name-->CT, 
<!--english motivation--> "for their contributions to the theory of optimum allocation of resources".
<!--misc-->
<p>
<!--misc-->
<H3>The Nobel Prize in Economic Sciences 1976</H3>
<!--misc-->
<!--name-->FRIEDMAN, 
<!--name-->MILTON, 
<!--misc-->U.S.A., 
<!--misc-->University 
<!--misc-->of 
<!--misc-->Chicago,
<!--misc-->Chicago, 
<!--name-->IL, 
<!--english motivation--> "for his achievements in the fields of consumption analysis, monetary history and theory and for his demonstration of the complexity  of stabilization policy".
<!--misc-->
<H3>The Nobel Prize in Economic Sciences 1977</H3>
<!--misc-->
<!--misc-->The 
<!--misc-->prize 
<!--misc-->was 
<!--misc-->divided 
<!--misc-->equally 
<!--misc-->between:
<p>
<!--misc-->
<!--name-->OHLIN, 
<!--name-->BERTIL, 
<!--misc-->Sweden, 
<!--misc-->Stockholm 
<!--misc-->School 
<!--misc-->of 
<!--misc-->Economics, 
<!--misc-->Stockholm, 
<!--misc-->and
<p>
<!--misc-->
<!--name-->MEADE, 
<!--name-->JAMES 
<!--misc-->E, 
<!--misc-->Great 
<!--misc-->Britain, 
<!--misc-->Cambridge 
<!--misc-->University, 
<!--misc-->Cambridge, 
<!--english motivation--> "for their pathbreaking contribution to the theory of international trade and  international capital movements".
<!--misc-->
<p>
<!--misc-->
<H3>The Nobel Prize in Economic Sciences 1978</H3>
<!--misc-->
<!--name-->SIMON, 
<!--name-->HERBERT 
<!--misc-->A., 
<!--misc-->U.S.A., 
<!--misc-->Carnegie-Mellon 
<!--misc-->University, 
<!--misc-->Pittsburgh, 
<!--name-->PA, 
<!--english motivation--> "for his pioneering research into the decision-making process within economic organizations".
<!--misc-->
<p>
<!--misc-->
